## Legacy document envelope

| Level | Fields and behavior |
| --- | --- |
| Page | `id`, `slug`, `title`, `description`, `visibility`, `content`, ownership/engagement/timestamps; `content` is a JSON string containing an ordered section array |
| Section | `id`, `display_order`, `section_type`, `heading`, `subheading`, `config`, optional `items`, optional frontend-only `last_edited_by` |
| Item | `id`, `section_id`, `display_order`, `icon`, `heading`, `subheading`, `image_url`, `link_url`, `config` |
| Config storage | Production input includes JSON-encoded strings and JSON objects; compatibility decoding must accept both and canonical output must use one object form |
| Identity | Legacy section/item IDs may be numbers or strings and are scoped to their parent page/section; copied pages can reuse IDs |
| Empty values | Empty pages are valid; empty visibility currently behaves as non-private and migrates explicitly to `public` |

Current page saves accept only positive numeric section IDs and registered
canonical types. Legacy string IDs and `features` therefore require a dedicated
migration adapter; they must not be made valid accidentally by weakening normal
write validation.

## Current shared presentation inventory

All shared presentation currently lives inside each section's `config` string.

| Field | Accepted/default behavior | Legacy alias |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `layout` | `left`, `center`, `right`, `wide`; default `center` | truthy `wide` means `wide` |
| `marginTop/Right/Bottom/Left` | numbers; default `0`; negative values are currently rendered | none |
| `paddingTop/Right/Bottom/Left` | numbers; default `0` | card-template `padding` expands to four sides |
| `animation` | `none`, `fade-in`, `slide-up`, `slide-left`, `slide-right`, `zoom-in`, `bounce`; default `none` | none |
| `animationIntensity` | `subtle`, `normal`, `dramatic`; default `normal` | none |
| `bg_color` | free string today; default empty | CTA also applies this inside its own surface |

`SectionFrame`, invoked by `BlockRenderer`, consumes the generated shared shell
through the compatibility adapter and owns outer layout, spacing, container
width, background, bounded content scale, animation, collapse, suspense, and one
shared move/copy/cut/delete toolbar. Blocks no longer render shared toolbars; six
families portal only renderer-specific actions into the frame toolbar. Renderers
retain semantic heading/subheading placement, inline content editing, item
controls, and empty states where their DOM contracts differ. Clipboard copy
keeps the complete section except interactive `records` and `result_summary`;
page duplicate does the same and forces the new page to `private`.

Renderer dispatch is exhaustive across the 19 canonical types. Stored legacy
`features` resolves to `feature_grid`; every other unknown or missing type renders
a content-safe visible error, and editors may remove it without exposing config.

The v1 typed shared-shell schema includes validated background, ordinary text,
`h1`, `h2`, and `h3` color sources; page palette-token references; bounded
`content_scale`; `collapsible`; and `default_collapsed`.
Viewer collapse state is permission-aware ephemeral state, not persisted viewer
data. It is keyed by page, section, and authoritative revision so rerenders
retain the local choice while reload, navigation, or a revision change restores
the authored default. Literal colors use a safe CSS subset; palette references
resolve only to declared page tokens through namespaced CSS variables. Resolvable
background/text pairs surface an editor contrast warning. The appearance editor
is a fixed, body-portaled popover that follows its toolbar anchor, flips above or
below according to available space, and remains bounded within the viewport.
Literal colors use the shared native color picker while inherit and palette-token
sources retain explicit controls.

## Section-specific compatibility matrix

Every type also accepts the shared presentation fields above.

| Canonical type | Section config and defaults | Items / special behavior |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `hero` | `background_image` (fallback banner), `videos[]`, `tint_color` (`#000000`), `tint_opacity` (`0.45`), `variant` (`1`) | legacy `video_url` becomes a one-entry video list; multi-video order is meaningful |
| `card_group` | shared only | common items; new heading/subheading defaults are `New Card` / `Description here` |
| `stat_cards` | shared only | common items; icon defaults to `Star` |
| `social_links` | `links[{icon,url}]`, default empty | config-backed list, not `PageItem` rows |
| `image_gallery` | `albums[{key,label}]` (fallback `all`), `default_card_width` (`regular`) | item config has `album` (`all`) and `width`; truthy item/section `wide` aliases to `wide` |
| `feature_grid` | shared only | common items; legacy section type `features` maps here |
| `cta` | shared plus `bg_color` | heading/subheading only; background is applied by outer renderer and CTA surface |
| `event_highlights` | shared only | common items use image, heading, subheading |
| `profile_card` | `banner_url`, `avatar_url`, `profile_name`, `profile_subtitle`, `description`, `checklist[]`, `links[{label,url}]` | fallback images/name/subtitle remain visible |
| `rich_text` | `content` HTML, default empty | inline author styles must round-trip; empty editor prompt is editor-only |
| `code_editor` | `code` (`""`), `language` (`typescript`), `filename` (`""`) | HTML/Markdown preview; copy/download are viewer actions |
| `data_sources` | shared only | management UI reads datasource APIs; environment values never enter fixtures or page broadcasts |
| `derived_section` | `datasource_id`, `column_map`, `row_overrides`, `row_key_column`, `card_template`, `component_type`, `component_version`, `bindings`, `style_overrides`, `component_group`, `event_hooks` | datasource rows are runtime projections, not persisted page items |
| `custom_section` | derived fields plus `custom_section_id` | saved `custom_sections` values are presets/datasource views, not page-section types |
| `form` | interactive shared definition fields; new default has name/email/message fields | records are sensitive runtime data and are cleared on copy/duplicate |
| `qa` | interactive fields plus `moderation` default `true`; question textarea default | public feed exposes only policy-approved records |
| `survey` | interactive fields; satisfaction scale and feedback defaults | default limit `1`, results after participation |
| `poll` | interactive fields; one radio choice default | effective per-user limit `1` |
| `vote` | interactive fields; one candidate radio default | confirmed ballot, effective per-user limit `1` |

Interactive shared definition fields are `status`, `submit_label`, `success_text`,
`result_visibility`, `response_limit`, `fields`, and `records`; optional
`moderation` and derived `result_summary` vary by type and authorization. Raw
records are never reusable design data.

## Item and designed-card inventory

- Common item fields are all independently editable depending on block type;
  unused fields still round-trip.
- Gallery item config owns `album` and width. Unknown item config keys must not
  be silently dropped during compatibility projection.
- `CardTemplate` includes width/height/aspect, zones, gaps, four margins, four
  paddings, image position/height, radius, style, overflow, content alignment,
  constrained custom CSS, and table flags.
- Legacy unified `padding` initializes all four padding sides only when the
  side-specific values are absent.
- Saved `custom_sections.section_type` production values are `table`, `cards`,
  and `component`. Component presets include string group IDs, bind maps,
  event-hook arrays, max width, and constrained custom CSS. These values must not
  be validated as the 19 page `SectionType` values.

## Current live and persistence paths

1. REST reads use the authorization-filtered `Page.Content` rollback projection
   until `PAGE_NORMALIZED_SECTION_READS` and the page-specific cutover gate select
   normalized definition/response rows. A normalized read never reads the
   rollback document.
2. Pages without the typed-ready flag serialize the section array through
   `PUT /pages/{id}`. Matched, flag-enabled pages use typed section CRUD/reorder
   and palette endpoints; whole-document definition changes then return `409`.
3. Typed services enforce centralized editor policy and generated contract
   validation before repositories lock page/section rows and check revisions.
4. Transactions update normalized definitions and the legacy document together.
   On response-migrated pages normalized response rows are authoritative and the
   document retains an answer-bearing rollback projection with hashed, never raw,
   idempotency material; other pages retain document response authority.
5. Successful writes invalidate page SEO cache state.
6. `page:update/page_updated` sends stable IDs/revisions in a content-free partial
   invalidation to `page:{id}` subscribers, excluding the HTTP sender.
7. `usePageData` refetches partial invalidations, holds updates during active
   editing, replays page subscriptions on reconnect, and refetches revisions.
8. `GET /config/section-contracts` publishes the embedded shared-shell and
   page-theme, normalized item/preset, and 19 per-type config JSON Schema 2020-12
   contracts without making them mutable data. Registry definitions derive their
   version, defaults, capabilities, config schema, and optional item schema from
   those contracts. Canonical interactive configs exclude runtime response data.

`ValidateContractValue` is the authoritative normalized-contract boundary. It
resolves only embedded schemas, validates contract defaults, rejects unknown
fields and unsafe CSS color literals, and returns errors without echoing user
config. `ValidateNormalizedSectionConfig` is intentionally not called by legacy
`ValidateContent`: object/string decoding, shell extraction, aliases, and runtime
record separation must happen first.

`backend/cmd/section-contract-gen` deterministically generates frontend and Go
section discriminators, shared-shell/config types, config-key maps, per-type DTOs,
versions/defaults, and capabilities from registry contracts. `go test ./...` and
frontend `npm run contracts:check` fail when either checked-in artifact drifts.
`DecodeNormalizedSectionConfig` rejects oversized, deeply nested, duplicate-key,
malformed, unknown-field, and schema-invalid JSON before returning a generated Go
DTO.

Frontend `PageSection<T>` is the generic normalized boundary; an unparameterized
`PageSection` remains the `LegacyPageSection` document envelope until normalized
persistence cuts over. `adaptLegacyPageSection` accepts object or string config,
canonicalizes `features`, separates shared shell, per-type config, interactive
runtime projections, and unknown quarantine, and retains numeric or string
legacy section/item keys. `SectionFrame` consumes that normalized shell for every
renderer, while the reverse projector feeds the current document save/render
path during the compatibility window. This adapter is structural; backend schema
validation remains authoritative before normalized persistence.

Normalized section writes retain the REST-authoritative flow with expected
revisions and stable server IDs. Same-section stale revisions conflict;
different-section writes converge independently. WebSocket payloads identify
affected resources and revisions but never include page content, preset config,
interactive answers, or idempotency keys.
`RequireExpectedSectionRevision` is the reusable fail-closed gate: missing or
invalid revisions are rejected, stale writes to one section conflict without
mutation, and writes to different sections advance independently. Normalized
repositories must apply it to a locked row in the same transaction as the write.

Phase 4 established the response-free normalized shadow. Phase 5 exposes it for
matched, feature-enabled pages while reads remain on the rollback projection.
`page_section_instances` and `page_section_instance_items` receive
stable server IDs while preserving page/section-scoped numeric-or-string legacy
keys, source order, display order, object/string config encoding, shell/config
separation, rich HTML, media, items, and unknown fields. Page creates and builder
updates write the document and shadow rows in one transaction; interactive
Phase 6 adds a separate page-scoped matched response-migration gate. When
`PAGE_NORMALIZED_INTERACTIVE_RESPONSES` is enabled, record mutations use locked
normalized rows and transactionally refresh the compatibility projection;
non-migrated pages continue to use the document path.

The bounded `page-section-shadow-backfill` command resumes by page ID. Each run
stores only canonical hashes, counts, field-name repair/quarantine metadata, and
mismatch codes. Invalid values remain in authoritative `pages.content` and in
non-public quarantine columns where a normalized row exists; operational
telemetry never echoes values. Unsupported sections receive structural
quarantine metadata. Response migration telemetry likewise stores only hashes,
counts, and mismatch codes.

`page-section-cutover` is the Phase 7 operational gate. It adds a consecutive
zero-diff observation, verifies normalized -> compatibility -> normalized
definition and response parity, records rollback-drill status, and evaluates a
non-destructive legacy-write retirement preflight. Normalized reads require the
matched definition/response migrations, zero quarantine, the configured minimum
run/window, and a matched drill. `PAGE_NORMALIZED_SECTION_READS=0` is the read
rollback switch. Whole-document compatibility saves remain enabled and counted
for one release window; retirement stays blocked by recent calls, incomplete
pages, non-empty dormant tables, or missing operator confirmation that external
clients and jobs no longer depend on `pages.content`.

Datasource-backed reusable `custom_sections` are now named section presets at
the API/type boundary. `/config/section-presets` and `preset_type` are preferred;
`/config/custom-sections` and `section_type` remain exact compatibility aliases.
Their `table`/`cards`/`component` discriminator remains distinct from the 19 page
section types and from normalized page-section snapshot presets.

## Canonical migration mappings

- Decode config object or JSON string to one object without double encoding.
- Map legacy `features` to `feature_grid` and retain the original spelling in
  migration audit/quarantine metadata until parity is proven.
- Store original numeric/string IDs as scoped legacy keys; generate new server
  primary keys rather than casting or reusing them globally.
- Normalize empty visibility to `public` only in the verified compatibility
  projector.
- Preserve unknown section, config, and item keys in quarantine/round-trip data
  until a versioned type migration owns them.
- Preserve ordering, empty content, negative spacing, inline rich-text colors,
  media URLs, preset references, and copied page-scoped ID collisions.

